communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Gregory formachelli (Fullerton Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Arrest records and affidavits

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rebecca Milligan

communications.subject: Re: Production Status of SB 1421 Files
communications.communication:
Dear SB1421 Requesters and interested parties,

It has come to my attention that the City of Fullerton has broken California’s Public Record’s Law, specifically related to SB1421, by denying you records which are quite clearly publicly disclosable.

In the link sent to you by Mea Klein, Assistant City Clerk, as provided to her by the City Attorney, you were told that there are 27 Officers "REQUESTED BY NAME, BUT NO DISCLOSABLE FILE AVAILABLE (27)”. This is patently false.

The City of Fullerton is currently suing me, my compatriot David and the blog Friends for Fullerton’s Future directly related to the findings on several of these officers.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/city-of-fullerton-is-suing-me-and-this-blog/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/city-of-fullerton-is-suing-me-and-this-blog/>

In looking at this list I can quite easily name Officers on that list who have disclosable records under SB1421 including but not limited to Kathryn Hamel, Paul Irish, Miguel “Sonny” Siliceo, Christopher Wren & Nathan Roesler.

A sustained finding was found against Hamel and one cannot simply unring that bell as seen in the recent Contra Costa County tentative decision (CASE NAME: RICHMOND POLICE VS. CITY OF RICHMOND <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Contra-Costa-Ruling-Case-MSN19-0169-2020-07-31.pdf>). 

This FFFF article related to Hamel is specifically mentioned in the lawsuit against myself and FFFF:

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullerton-police-cut-a-deal-to-bypass-the-law/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullerton-police-cut-a-deal-to-bypass-the-law/>

Christopher Wren had a sustained finding against for dishonesty related to a workplace affair with a subordinate. In IA Case #17-0038 one of the sustained findings against Officer Wren is as follows:

“6. On December 17, 2017, when Lieutenant Cleggett asked you about your whereabouts, you dishonestly stated to Lieutenant Cleggett that you had been on the phone with your wife the entire time and did not notice Lieutenant Cleggett’s text message.”

This statement of dishonesty was directly related to misconduct as outlined in the timeline of Wren’s activities and being in violation of policy. 

Likewise with Christopher Wren, this article is specifically listed in the lawsuit being waged against myself and FFFF:

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/what-happened-to-officer-christopher-wren/

The idea that the city attorney is unaware of the sustained findings against their officers which are disclosable under SB1421 is laughable when those very stories are being used by the same attorneys as evidence in a lawsuit where the city seeks a prior restraint against myself and FFFF.

The blog has likewise published stories on how Paul Irish was terminated for dishonesty;

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullertons-veritable-serpico-problem/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullertons-veritable-serpico-problem/>

Miguel “Sonny” Siliceo admitted in the plea deal that he both used excessive force and falsified a police report.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/sonnys-admission-guilt/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/sonnys-admission-guilt/>

Nathan Roesler filed a false report with the City of Placentia which resulted in an innocent man being arrested for a crime that wasn’t committed against Roesler. This was referred to the District Attorney for prosecution.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/another-possible-cover-up-by-fpd/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/another-possible-cover-up-by-fpd/>

These are the cases which are readily and easily pointed out which I believe to be disclosable under SB1421 which calls all of the other officers on the list into question. The City is blatantly lying to you, your organizations and agencies as well as the public and concerned entities about disclosable records despite being in a separate lawsuit over these very violations of SB1421.

They are likewise violating the law in regards to the officer whose records are "PENDING; NOT YET PRODUCED (3)”. The incident in Corbett’s case was from 2016 and Paez’s was in 2017. The timeline has long passed for required production in both of these cases.

If you are honestly seeking these records and others from the City of Fullerton you will likely have no recourse but to seek remedies in order to get to the truth. I have already been forced to take this route unfortunately.

Thank you for your time and I wish you all the best in your efforts.

Sincerely,

Joshua Ferguson
Host, The Hourly Struggle
Writer, Friends for Fullerton’s Future
Concerned Citizen

communications.subject: Fullerton Production Status of SB 1421 Files
communications.communication:
Dear SB 1421 requesters and interested parties:
You have each recently received a mass email communication from an individual with whom the City of Fullerton is currently engaged in civil litigation, Joshua Ferguson.  The email contained inaccuracies about the City's responses to Public Records requests.  The City would like to correct certain information and assure you and other members of the public of its commitment to transparency and compliance with legal requirements for the disclosure of public records, including certain peace officer records recently made public under SB 1421, which is codified at Penal Code section 832.7.  Of course, the City cannot respond as to any specifics about any individual officers referenced, due to privacy.

Disclosable use of force files:
Not all use of force investigation files are disclosable under SB 1421.  SB 1421 only allows the disclosure of those files involving uses of force that have resulted in death or "great bodily injury."  Pen. Code section 832.7(b)(1)(A)(ii).  "Great bodily injury" means "significant or substantial physical injury."  Pen. Code section 16600.  Examples of "great bodily injury" include: broken bones, People v. Villarreal (1985) 173 Cal.App.3d 1136, 1141; gunshot wounds, People v. Mendias (1993) 17 Cal.App.4th 195; and a dog bite, People v. Frazier (2009) 173 Cal. App. 4th 613, 618.  SB 1421 also mandates the disclosure of investigation files involving a peace officer or custodial officer's discharge of a firearm at a civilian.  See Pen. Code section 832.7(b)(1)(A)(i).

Disclosable dishonesty files:
Not all dishonesty investigation files are disclosable under SB 1421.  SB 1421 only allows the disclosure of "sustained finding[s] . . . [of] dishonesty by a peace officer or custodial officer directly relating to the reporting, investigation, or prosecution of a crime, or directly relating to the reporting of, or investigation of misconduct by, another peace officer or custodial officer, including but not limited to, any sustained finding of perjury, false statements, filing false reports, destruction, falsifying, or concealing of evidence."  See Cal. Penal Code section 832.7(b)(1)(C) (emphasis added).
The Legislature intended to provide the public access to cases involving dishonesty, where an officer "is proven to have planted evidence, committed perjury, or otherwise been dishonest in the reporting, investigation, or prosecution of a crime."  Assembly Committee on Public Safety, Analysis of SB 1421 (June 26, 2018).

In order for acts of dishonesty to be disclosable under SB 1421, there must also have been a "sustained" finding of dishonesty.  A "sustained finding" is defined as "a final determination by an investigating agency, commission, board, hearing officer, or arbitrator, as applicable, following an investigation and opportunity for an administrative appeal pursuant to Sections 3304 and 3304.5 of the Government Code, that the actions of the peace officer or custodial officer were found to violate law or department policy."  Pen. Code section 832.8 (emphasis added).

If an officer investigated for the type dishonesty or sexual assault that is disclosable under SB 1421 resigns prior to a sustained finding, his or her file is not disclosable.

Although the email that you received referred to a specific court ruling (Richmond Police Officers' Ass'n v. City of Richmond), that ruling was only tentative (not final) and was only the ruling of one Superior Court Judge in Contra Costa County.  The City of Fullerton is located in Orange County, and is not subject to those courts or their rulings.  However, even a ruling in Orange County would not have been determinative, as facts in different cases may lead to different results, and a single judge's opinion is not required to be followed by other judges, until there is some binding opinion of higher courts.  In fact, in City of Richmond, that court found that the employer and an officer could not reverse sustained findings of dishonesty or sexual assault through a negotiated settlement, after the conclusion of a formal hearing process.  In circumstances where a final, formal hearing has not been held, the court acknowledged that there would be no "sustained findings" and hence such records are "not disclosable under SB 1421."  (The City of Richmond court also noted that investigations of dishonesty involving subjects not specifically listed in Penal Code section 832.7 are also not disclosable).

Regardless of the inapplicability of the City of Richmond opinion in Orange County, the City of Fullerton's disclosure of its records under SB 1421 does follow the same principles.

The City is committed to providing all records that it is required and permitted to release to the public relating to peace officers.  It has been working hard to review and release all records newly made releasable since the enactment of SB 1421, and will continue to do so. The City has produced 26 SB 1421 files; has partially produced 13 additional SB 1421 files; and has 2 SB 1421 files pending review (one of which awaits resolution of administrative or other proceedings).  The City's SB 1421 productions are available at www.cityoffullerton.com/sb1421<http://www.cityoffullerton.com/sb1421>, and a copy of the summary chart detailing the progress of the City's SB 1421 review and production is posted therein.

If you have any questions or concerns about your requests or the City's production thereto, please contact the City Clerk's Office or the City Attorney's Office.

Jones & Mayer

Fullerton, California 92835

title: Public Records Request – Interrogation & Investigation Records: Michael Crowe (Stephanie Crowe Murder; Jan 1998)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Public Records Request – Interrogation & Investigation Records: Michael Crowe (Stephanie Crowe Murder; Jan 1998)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to public records relating to the criminal investigation and interrogation of Michael Crowe, age 14, in connection with the murder of his sister, Stephanie Crowe, in January 1998, in Escondido, CA.

Requested Records:

1. Complete video and/or audio recordings of all interrogations of Michael Crowe, including multiple sessions conducted between January 21–23, 1998.


2. Transcripts or written summaries of those interrogations, if available.


3. Interrogation and investigation memos, police reports, indices or logs summarizing the interviews and collection of evidence.


4. Any internal reviews, assessments, or complaints regarding interrogation methods used in connection with the Crowe case.


5. Correspondence relating to media or external inquiries, including any communication with Court TV, Oprah, or other journalists regarding the case.

 Identifying Details:

Incident: Murder of Stephanie Crowe; Michael became the focus of multiple extended interrogations.

Approx. Dates: January 21 through January 23, 1998.

Jurisdiction: Escondido Police Department, San Diego County.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brown Pearl

title: Cleveland Police Department: Social media settings

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Cleveland Police Department: Social media settings
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

This request seeks records relating to the Facebook page located at https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept. An example of what each of these records look like is attached and available at https://bit.ly/facebookfoia.

In order to access the requested information, you will first need to take the following steps:

1. Log into the page account or a Facebook account with managerial access to the Facebook page. For information on this type of access, see: https://www.facebook.com/help/187316341316631.)
2. "Switch" to the page account. To do so, click your profile photo in the top right, then click "See all profiles", then select the Page you want to switch into. (See the instructions here: https://www.facebook.com/help/123930246348340).
3. Click "Professional dashboard" on the left, or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/?sk=professional_dashboard

I request the following information:

1. The "Page and Tagging" information. Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=timeline&privacy_source=timeline_gear_menu. 

2. The list of blocked users. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block users" 
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

3. The list of blocked Pages. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block Pages" 
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

4. The list of "Moderation Assist" criteria. This information is accessible by following either of these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard" and then click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen.
(b) Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist

5. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has certain keywords", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has certain keywords").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has certain keywords"
(d) On the right side of the "Keywords" menu, click the ellipsis menu ("...")
(e) Click "Copy list" from the dropdown menu.
(f) Provide the information from the list.

6. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has specific links", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has specific links").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has links to specific sites."
(d) Provide the information from the "Added sites" list.

7. The list of people with Facebook access. From the "Professional dashboard" page (https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/?sk=professional_dashboard), click "Page Access" on the left side of the screen. Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=profile_access

8. The list of moderation actions in the Activity log. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard."
(b) Click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist).
(c) Click "Activity log" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_activity_log).
(c) From the dropdown menu labeled "Visible comments", select "Hidden comments".
(d) Continue scrolling down until the complete list is loaded.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

Moe Clark

communications.subject: DC Freedom of Information Act Request: Fleet Management Administration and Rivian
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the DC Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Information including but not limited to documents like registration reports, procurement agreements, contracts, about D.C. government owned and operated Rivian vehicle with number "98 16037" and Washington, D.C. license plate number "DC 16037" used for. 
I also request documents pertaining to the purchasing and maintenance of Rivian vehicles and any documents containing the number of total Rivian vehicles in the D.C. fleet.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Elijah Pittman

communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: R012258-070125
communications.communication:
Dear Elijah Pittman, 
 
 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of July 01, 2025, Reference # R012258-070125 
 
 
 
I send this note with regard to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request that you submitted to the DPW - Department of Public Works and assigned as Request Number R012258-070125 received on 7/1/2025. 
As you may know, DPW - Department of Public Works is required to respond to your FOIA request within fifteen (15) business days of its receipt.  See D.C. Official Code § 2-532(c)(2011).  However, under certain circumstances, D.C. Official Code § 2-532(d)(2011) authorizes the District to extend, by ten (10) additional days, the deadline by which it must respond to a FOIA request.  One of the circumstances provided by that statute is a case in which the District needs additional time to search for, collect and examine voluminous amounts of records and/or consult with an additional D.C. agency.  Pursuant to the above-referenced statute, the District has extended, by ten (10) days, the deadline by which it must respond to your FOIA request. We anticipate responding to your FOIA request on, or before 8/6/2025. 
Please know that, under D.C. Official Code § 2-537 and 1 DCMR 412, you have the right to appeal this response to the Mayor or to the Superior Court of the District of Columbia. If you elect to appeal to the Mayor, your appeal must be in writing and contain “Freedom of Information Act Appeal” or “FOIA Appeal” in the subject line of the letter as well on the outside of the envelope. The appeal must include (1) a copy of the original request; (2) a copy of any written denial; (3) a statement of the circumstances, reasons, and/or arguments advanced in support of disclosure; and (4) a daytime telephone number, and e-mail and/or U.S. Mail address at which you can be reached. The appeal must be mailed to: The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit, FOIA Appeal; 1350 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 316, Washington, D.C. 20004. Electronic versions of the same information can instead be e-mailed to The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit at foia.mayor@dc.gov 
 
 The following only applies to the Office of the Attorney General OAG: 
 Please note that under DC Code § 2-537(a-2), “[a]ny person denied the right to inspect a public record in the possession of the Attorney General may institute proceedings in the Superior Court of the District of Columbia for injunctive or declaratory relief, or for an order to enjoin the public body from withholding the record and to compel the production of the requested record.” 
Thank you. 
Jacqueline Williams 
Department of Public Works

communications.subject: RE: DC Freedom of Information Act Request #R012258-070125

Good afternoon Jackie, 

I hope that you are well. I apologize for not seeing your message requesting to call sooner, but when I tried to call both numbers earlier this week I couldn't get through to anybody. I understand that the district extended my FOIA request and I seriously appreciate the District's commitment to fulfilling the request. If you still think a call is necessary please feel free to call me at my cell which is 301.605.0311. I can typically almost always pick-up, but I'm specifically in the office Monday through Wednesday from 10:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. 

Thank you again for working with me on this, 
Elijah Pittman
Investigative Reporting Workshop

I'm following up on the following DC Freedom of Information Act request, copied below, and originally submitted on June 10, 2025. communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: R012258-070125
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
Dear Elijah Pittman, Thank you for speaking with me today. You clarified your request indicating that you are in possession of photos of the vehicle that is the subject of your request-- a DC Department of Transportation vehicle. This letter acknowledges and responds to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request #R012258-070125 to the DC Department of Public Works (DPW). You requested the following records: “Information including but not limited to documents like registration reports, procurement agreements, contracts, about D.C. government owned and operated Rivian vehicle with number "98 16037" and Washington, D.C. license plate number "DC 16037" used for. I also request documents pertaining to the purchasing and maintenance of Rivian vehicles and any documents containing the number of total Rivian vehicles in the D.C. fleet.” DPW provides municipal services in two distinct program areas: solid waste management and parking enforcement. Both contribute to making District streets and public spaces clean, safe, attractive, and accessible. DPW's Solid Waste Management Administration performs a number of daily operations including trash and recycling collection, sanitation education and enforcement, graffiti removal, public litter can service, fall leaf collection, and street and alley cleaning. DPW's Parking Enforcement Management Administration enforces the District's on-street parking laws. Approximately 200 parking officers monitor 17,000 meters and 3,500 blocks of residential zoned parking. In addition to routine enforcement, the Parking Enforcement Management Administration is charged with booting and towing operations and with removing abandoned and dangerous vehicles from public and private property. Behind the scenes, DPW's Fleet Management Administration supports municipal operations by procuring, fueling, and maintaining thousands of District government vehicles, from sedans to heavy equipment. Some vehicles are managed and maintained independently by certain agencies. Fleet Management also is responsible for purchasing environmentally friendly, alternative-fuel vehicles (AFV) for the city. Please be advised that DPW maintains information partially responsive to your request. Specifically, DPW is aware of fifty-six (56) Rivian vehicles within the District’s fleet. However, the District of Columbia Department of Transportation manages and maintains all the vehicles. Your FOIA requests concerning procurement agreements and contracts should be submitted to the DC Office of Procurement, FOIA Officer Jeremiah Regan, 441 4th Street NW, Washington, DC 20001, email: jeremiah.regan@dc.gov , phone: (202) 727-0252. Your FOIA requests related to vehicle registrations should be sent to DC Department of Motor Vehicles Pamela Washington, Assistant General Counsel, District of Columbia Department of Motor Vehicles, 95 M Street, SW, Washington, DC 20024-3622, phone (202) 729-7113; email: pamela.washington@dc.gov. (mailto:pamela.washington@dc.gov) Your requests related to maintenance should be sent to Nana Bailey-Thomas, Esq., Hearings/FOIA Officer, Office of the General Counsel, at the District Department of Transportation, 250 M Street, S.E., Suite 800, Washington, D.C. 20003; phone: (202) 673-6811; Email: nana.bailey@dc.gov. (mailto:nana.bailey@dc.gov) Therefore, FOIA request #R012258-070125 is . GRANTED IN PART Please note, under D.C. Official Code § 2-537 and 1 DCMR 412, you have the right to appeal this response to the Mayor or to the Superior Court of the District of Columbia. If you elect to appeal to the Mayor, your appeal must be in writing and contain “Freedom of Information Act Appeal” or “FOIA Appeal” in the subject line of the letter as well on the outside of the envelope. The appeal must include (1) a copy of the original request; (2) a copy of any written denial; (3) a statement of the circumstances, reasons, and/or arguments advanced in support of disclosure; and (4) a daytime telephone number, and e-mail and/or U.S. Mail address at which you can be reached. The appeal must be mailed to: The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit, FOIA Appeal; 1350 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 316, Washington, D.C. 20004. Electronic versions of the same information can instead be e-mailed to The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit at foia.mayor@dc.gov Further, you must forward a copy of all appeal materials to the Freedom of Information Officer of the involved agency or to the agency head if there is no designated Freedom of Information Officer.  Failure to follow these administrative steps will delay the processing and commencement of a response to your appeal. Sincerely, /s/ Jacqueline Williams Assistant General Counsel Department of Public Works

title: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Eatonville Police Department)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Eatonville Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

title: FOIL Request – Pedro Hernandez Interrogation & Case Records (Etan Patz Case, 2012)

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: FOIL Request – Pedro Hernandez Interrogation & Case Records (Etan Patz Case, 2012)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to and copies of all public records related to the investigation, interrogation, and prosecution of Pedro Hernandez, arrested in 2012 for the 1979 disappearance of Etan Patz.
Specifically, I am requesting:

1. All interrogation video and audio recordings of Pedro Hernandez from the NYPD and affiliated departments, including:

Pre-Miranda questioning

Post-Miranda statements

Any internal notes or summaries of those interviews


2. All detective reports, field notes, and memoranda related to his arrest and interviews


3. Communications between the NYPD and the Manhattan District Attorney’s Office concerning:

Admissibility of confessions

Legal strategy or trial preparation


4. Any policy memos or training documents revised or distributed in response to this case


5. Documents or correspondence related to any review, reconsideration, or internal audit following the 2025 appellate court decision overturning Hernandez’s conviction.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brown Pearl

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
July 2, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 165182-98158068@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015416-061624 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

A log of all emails to/from the Vanessa Hernandez, Special Assistant to the CEO, from June 1, 2024 to June 14, 2024. 

1. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 
RESPONSE : The Chicago Public Schools (CPS) FOIA Office has reviewed your request and determined that, as currently written, it is unduly burdensome beyond the public interest. The CPS FOIA Office has conducted a preliminary e-discovery search with the parameters set forth in this request, which yielded 1,774 search results. Due to the nature of the email search, in seeking two weeks’ worth of the CPS Special Assistant to the CEO’s email account without a filter by subject matter or keyword, subject line and sender and recipient lines are extremely likely to contain student and personal email addresses, identities of parents communicating with their child’s school, details pertaining to pending investigatory, predecisional, or attorney client privileged matters, and other student information which would require a careful and timely review of not only each of the 1,774 lines of metadata pulled in the log, but the emails themselves in order to determine if any portion of the data is exempt from disclosure. Accordingly, reviewing the requested records would require numerous staff hours and therefore, as your FOIA request is currently written, the dedication of staff and/or resources is unduly burdensome on the daily operations of the CPS beyond the public interest. This is not a denial of your request. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/3(g), we are asking that you narrow your request, in writing, to more manageable proportions.  If you do not modify or revise your request to more manageable proportions within five (5) business days, your request will be considered denied. If you do seek to narrow this request, you may to specify keywords or a subject matter for which you seek records, modify the request to seek a log of emails between Ms. Hernandez and other specified individuals, and/or limit the timeframe of the search. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

Dear Miriam Bhimani: RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015416-061624 Thank you for using the Chicago Public Schools FOIA Center. You requested the following: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires. 

Sincerely, 

Miriam Bhimani 

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fchicago-public-schools-3121%252Fcps-email-log-special-assistant-to-the-ceo-165182%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAATZ6_n4zL9LUQrOAhSu0BQ7O8%3A1sJ2F2%3Acjodi_ya6WZT1c6ZvhNa4kjwDLlBZ2_naUBsEEbOUgE RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please note that certain private information (employee ID numbers, personal email addresses, personal phone numbers, medical information, birthdates, etc.) was redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7. Specifically, section 7(1)(b) which exempts certain private information as defined by section 2(c-5) and section 7(1)(c) which exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subject of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. Student/parent information has been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

communications.subject: Saint Charles Police Department - Police Record Request PD2025-427: Confirmation
communications.communication:
Dear Requestor, 
  
 The St. Charles City Police Department Records Division received your open records request pursuant to Missouri's Sunshine Law, Chapter 610, RSMo on Monday, June 16, 2025.  
  
 Your request reference number is Request Number: PD2025-427  
 Your security key is F3DA7570  
  
 Please have both reference numbers available when communicating with our staff regarding your request.  
  
 Three Business Day Notice Requirement: 
The requested records are not immediately available for dissemination or inspection. This department is required to notify you that additional research time will be required to fulfill the request. This correspondence satisfies the Sunshine Law's notice requirement within the required three-business-day period. § 610.023.3, RSMo. 
 
Estimated Time for Completion: 
The majority of our requests are fulfilled within seven business days. Some requests require additional research time due to their scope or complexity. We will conduct an initial review of your request. If we estimate that the request will be fulfilled within seven business days, we will not send an updated time estimate. However, if we estimate that the request will take longer than seven business days, we will provide an updated time estimate that provides a detailed justification for the additional research time. 
 
Billing: 
This department will charge fees for copies and research time required for fulfilling records requests at the actual cost of research time. § 610.026, RSMo. The Missouri Supreme Court recently determined that "staff time is the time required to provide access to public records maintained on computer facilities, recording tapes or disks, videotapes or films, pictures, maps, slides, graphics, illustrations or similar audio or visual items." Gross v. Parson, 624 S.W.3d 877, 884-89 (Mo. 2021) (internal quotations omitted). You will only be charged for copies and staff research time as permitted by Missouri law. 
 
Our team will forward a bill estimate to your attention once we have calculated the permissible costs and fees. This department will not provide the responsive records until receipt of payment. § 610.026.2, RSMo. 
 
We appreciate your patience as we review, research, and fulfill your open records request. 
  
 Thank you,  
  
 Saint Charles Police Department 
1781 Zumbehl Road
Saint Charles, MO 63303 
(636) 940-4619

title: William M. Beecher (May 27, 1933 – February 9, 2024)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: William M. Beecher (May 27, 1933 – February 9, 2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into investigative journalist William M. Beecher (May 27, 1933 – February 9, 2024). His death is widely-known and widely reported; as such, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. For example, you may find his New York Times obituary at the following link: https://www.nytimes.com/2024/02/18/business/media/william-beecher-dead.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC. My request includes but is not limited to 137, 157, 176, 177, 183, 184, 188, and 214 files. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents, as the FOIA requires.

I request that I be properly classified as a media requester. I am an investigative journalist who has written numerous articles on topics of public interest for the Daily Beast, the Asia Times, Responsible Statecraft, the National Interest, Reason Magazine, America Magazine and the Armenian Weekly, and I am requesting these documents in an editorial capacity. Please contact me if you have any questions about my media status.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1620220-000
communications.communication:
To whom this may concern,

My name is Matthew Petti and I am writing in response to my FOIA request number 1620220-000. Thank you so much for your prompt response.

In your letter dated 6 March 2024, you write that "additional records potentially responsive to your subject may exist. If this release of previously processed material does not satisfy your request, you may request an additional search for records."

I would like to formally advise that I would like an additional search for records. Thank you again for your prompt attention to this matter. If possible, please let me know if you've received this message.

Best regards,
Matthew

communications.subject: FOIA Request 1620220-001/William Beecher
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

We're contacting you in reference to the FOIPA request number included in the subject line of this email.  The FBI located approximately 2,083 pages potentially responsive to your request. 

Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system:
Extra-small track requests (0-50 pages) current average time is approximately 8 months to complete;
Small track requests (51-250 pages) current average time is approximately 36 months to complete;
Medium track requests (251-500 pages) current average time is approximately 44 months to complete;
Large track requests (501-4,999 pages) current average time is approximately 67 months to complete; and
Extra-large track requests (5,000+ pages) current average time is approximately 79 months to complete.

The current average time to complete your large track request is at least 67 months. Reducing the scope of your request may accelerate the processing, allow for a timelier receipt of the information you seek, and reduce the duplication costs, if applicable.  Would you be willing to consider reducing the scope of your request to place it in a smaller, potentially faster processing track?

Please let us know if this is something you would be interested in further discussing. If you chose to narrow the scope of your request, you will be able to request remaining material via a new FOIPA request submission at the completion of this request, subject to applicable fees.

Respectfully,

Negotiation Team
Federal Bureau of Investigation
Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov<mailto:Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov>

communications.communication:
Dear Negotiation Team,

I hope this message finds you well. My name is Matthew Petti and I am writing with regard to my FOIA request number 1620220-001/William Beecher. Do you have any suggestions on how to reduce the scope of the request? Otherwise, I am happy to leave it in the large track.

Sincerely,
Matthew

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1620220-001
communications.communication:
Good morning,
Thank you for your email concerning the scope reduction of this request.  Unfortunately, we are limited on what we can discuss since the potentially responsive pages haven’t been reviewed by a FOIA analyst.
After further review, the potentially responsive pages are within the date range of 1953-1987.
We recommend the following options:

We could narrow the scope of this request by limiting to a specific date range within 1953-1987.

We could reduce the scope of this request by limiting to approximately 50 potentially responsive pages.  This request would move to the simple track with an average time to complete of approximately 8 months.

We could reduce the scope of this request by limiting to approximately 250 potentially responsive pages.  This request would move to the small track with an average time to complete of approximately 36 months.

We could reduce the scope of this request by limiting to approximately 500 potentially responsive pages.  This request would move to the medium track with an average time to complete of approximately 44 months.

Please let us know how you would like to move forward with reducing the scope of your request.
Respectfully,

Negotiation Team
Federal Bureau of Investigation
Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov<mailto:Fbi.foipa.negotiation@fbi.gov>

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: 25-PRA-208 - MuckRock News (Andrew Ma)
communications.communication:
Good morning,



This is in response to your request for records from the California Correctional Health Care Services (CCHCS) under the California Public Records Act (CPRA), which was received in our office on July 7, 2025, and the response was sent to you on July 17, 2025.



Specifically, you requested the following:

Requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

  *   Full names
  *   Job titles
  *   Assigned correctional facility
  *   Government-issued email addresses
  *   Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
  *   Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.
Please see the attached identified document:


  *   CCHCS Mental Health Employee Listing 7.7.25


Please note that direct desk numbers were not disclosed within the above noted records as this information is protected from disclosure by the terms of the Public Records Act, including Government Code Sections 7927.700, 7927.705, and the Information Practices Act of 1977, specifically Civil Code Sections 1798.3(a) and 1798.24.  However, a phone number was provided in the "Department Phone Number" column for instances where the employee's work facility has a general phone number available to the public.

If you require any further assistance, you may contact us via e-mail at CCHCSHealthPRAS@CDCR.ca.gov<mailto:CCHCSHealthPRAS@CDCR.ca.gov>, or by regular mail at:

California Correctional Health Care Services
Attention: PRA Coordinator, Building C
P.O. Box 588500
Elk Grove, CA  95758

Sincerely,
[Logo  Description automatically generated]
G. Henderson
PRA Coordinator

GH/ip
CCHCSHealthPRAs@cdcr.ca.gov<mailto:CCHCSHealthPRAs@cdcr.ca.gov>

title: Delaware State Police Open Records Request - Quattrone Center

communications.subject: Delaware Freedom of Information Act Request: Delaware State Police Open Records Request - Quattrone Center
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Delaware Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Delaware State Police,

Dear State Police,

Pursuant to Delaware Code Title 29, Chapter 100 of the Freedom of Information Act, I am requesting access to all records related to the purchase of field drug testing supplies and technologies (used to identify unknown substances that are potentially contraband) by your agency from January 1, 2016 to the present. 

1.	Specifically, I am requesting contracts your agency or department has with providers of drug testing kit or device providers (such as colorimetric or presumptive field tests or testing insurance), or any other records indicating the quantity, cost, vendor, and model of each item or system purchased. This request includes materials related to but not limited to the following:
o	Colorimetric or presumptive field test kits, such as: 
	NIK Public Safety kits 
	Sirchie NARK II kits
	Field Forensics DABIT kits
	Mistral drug identification/detection kits
	M.M.C. International B.V. presumptive drug tests
	TN Scientific Mandelin Reagent drug testing kits
	Macherey-Nagel MEDI-TEST
	Any other colorimetric or presumptive kits
o	Instrument-based technologies, including: 
	Raman spectroscopy devices
	Infrared (IR) spectroscopy devices
	Ion mobility spectrometry (IMS) devices
	Mass spectrometry (MS) devices
	Any other field-portable drug identification technologies
1.	Total annual budget allocated to the purchase or acquisition of such drug testing kits or devices.
2.	Spending information (such as invoices, purchase orders, or receipts) for any presumptive drug testing kits or devices.
3.	This request does not include urine, blood, or other tests designed to identify drug compounds in the human body. This request is made as part of an academic research project examining the use and cost of field drug testing technologies by law enforcement and correctional agencies nationwide. If possible, I request that the records be provided in electronic format (PDF, Excel, or CSV).

If any part of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, including the specific exemption(s) relied upon. If the requested records are available in part, I request access to all segregable portions. Should there be any material cost (defined as more than $100) associated with providing the requested information, please provide me with an estimate before proceeding with any work.

Please contact me at QuattroneResearch@law.upenn.edu or 215-746-1251 if you have any questions or require clarification. Thank you for your time and assistance.

Sincerely,

 
Ross Miller
Assistant Director
Quattrone Center for the Fair Administration of Justice

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Rudenberg, a citizen of Delaware, in coordination with Ross Miller.

Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-2018-083302 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a FOIAonline account at https://foiaonline.gov.  This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request. (https://foiaonline.regulations.gov/) 
Provisions of the Act allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations outlined on the DHS website, https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations. By submitting your request, you have agreed to pay up to $25.00 in applicable processing fees, if any fees associated with your request exceed this amount, CBP shall contact you; however, the first 100 pages are free. (https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2016/11/22/2016-28095/freedom-of-information-act-regulations) 
Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 
For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. (http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia) 
Sincerely, 
U.S. Customs and Border Protection

title: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart
communications.communication:
Subject: ALPR Audit Reports Review by Chief of Police Schenita Stewart

Dear FOIA Officer,

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request records related to the Evanston Police Department’s (EPD) use of Flock Safety automated license plate reader (ALPR) technology. This request is based on a recent communication from Schenita Stewart, Chief of Police regarding state surveillance and Evanston’s Welcoming City Ordinance:

“To ensure compliance with the Welcoming City Ordinance and protect community trust, I have assigned a dedicated supervisor to oversee all aspects of ALPR usage within EPD. Furthermore, we conduct regular organizational and network audits, which I personally review. EPD also operates under a clear and established policy governing ALPR use, reinforcing both accountability and transparency.”

According to the City of Evanston's website page on the "Welcoming City Ordinance" (Ordinance 17-O-25):

"Key updates to the Ordinance include:

Data Protection: Prohibiting the sharing of city databases or information with federal immigration agencies, or with third parties unless they certify against its use for civil immigration enforcement.

Expanded Safeguards: Clarifying that City officials will not participate in civil immigration enforcement by any agency or personnel, including private contractors. The City will continue to comply with a valid criminal warrant.

Closing Loopholes: Strengthening policies to eliminate exceptions that previously allowed limited City involvement in immigration enforcement under certain conditions.

Support for Immigrants: Codifying practices that assist crime victims in obtaining specific visas and providing immigration resource information through public services like 311.

Safe Public Buildings: The City is now tasked with developing policies for its public facilities that prioritize limiting immigration enforcement operations on their premises to the fullest extent allowed by law."

In light of this statement made by Schenita Stewart, Chief of Police, along with the updates to Evanston's Welcoming City Ordinance, and in accordance with Illinois law (625 ILCS 5/2-130), which prohibits sharing automated license plate reader ALPR data with out-of-state agencies for purposes such as interfering with reproductive health access or enforcing immigration laws, I request full transparency for the following:

1) Any records showing review or oversight of Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR Organization or Network audit reports by the Chief of Police Schenita Stewart from January 1, 2024, to the present - including emails, memos, meeting notes, audit summaries, annotations, or briefings demonstrating the Stewart’s direct involvement in reviewing audit data.

2) Any communications between the Chief of Police Schenita Stewart and Evanston Police Department supervisors or Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR administrators regarding network audit findings that raised questions or concerns, including but not limited to:
    a) Access by out-of-state agencies (e.g., AL, FL, IN, KY, MO, NC, TX, etc) 
    b) Federal agency involvement (e.g., DHS, HSI, ICE, CBP, etc)
    c) References to abortion or reproductive health care (e.g., abortion, women, woman, pregnant, pp, planned parenthood, etc)
    d) References to immigration enforcement (e.g., immigration, border patrol, 287g, etc)
    e) Search reasons lacking case numbers or specific descriptions (e.g., inv, p, m, zz, training, test, ab501, invest, narcotics, drugs, 123abv, etc)

3) Any internal protocols or policies that describe the role of the Evanston Police Department’s chief or supervisors in reviewing Flock Safety automated license plate reader ALPR audits and identifying potentially inappropriate use, particularly regarding compliance with Illinois statutes and Evanston’s Welcoming City Ordinance.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Niles Coalition

communications.subject: RE: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request #25-1704
communications.communication:
Hello, as a requester under the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (5 ILCS 140), I remind you of the following:

- Under 5 ILCS 140/3(d), a public body must respond to a FOIA request within 5 business days.
- Under 5 ILCS 140/3(e), a one-time extension of no more than 5 additional business days is permitted, provided proper notice is given.

After that, any additional delay requires the requester's consent. I only agreed to a single extension on June 17, 2025, setting a revised overdue deadline of June 23, 2025.
Subsequent extensions requested on:

- June 26, 2025
- July 7, 2025

were not consented to, and therefore violate the requirements of the Illinois FOIA statute.

communications.communication:

I would like a spreadsheet containing all the academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Sincerely,

Anonymous

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request: Academic Dishonesty Study (University Of Houston); IR10498
communications.communication:
Requestor, my office received your request below. You have asked for “a spreadsheet containing all the academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college.”

In accordance with Texas Government Code § 552.222, the University seeks clarification regarding your request. You ask for information concerning all academic dishonesty reports by college for a 4 year period. Academic dishonesty information that includes personally identifiable information about a student is protected from disclosure by the federal law FERPA. Please clarify whether you are seeking information about the number of reports only. If not, please explain what you are seeking.  Please note that the University cannot provide student record information in response to a Public Information Act request.
Please simply respond to this e-mail to provide clarification.  The University is required to inform you that if you fail to respond to this e-mail seeking to clarify your request within 61 days, your request will be considered withdrawn. Regards, Jennifer Bloom
____________________________________
Jennifer E. Bloom

The total number of academic dishonesty reports for University of Houston for each of the following years:
2021-22

David May, Ph.D.

Department of Sociology

title: NASA Return to Office Implementation plan

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: NASA Return to Office Implementation plan
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. any Return to Office (RTO) Implementation plan(s) submitted by NASA to OPM and/or OMB in response to the January 20, 2025, Presidential Memorandum (PM) "Return to In-Person Work" and its implementing guidance
2. any subsequent communications between NASA and OPM and/or OMB regarding the review/approval/disapproval of NASA's RTO implementation plan(s)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

William James Cawley

title: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Sixth Judicial District

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: New Mexico IPRA Request: Police disciplinary files for officers/deputies in Sixth Judicial District
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.

- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Bowling

Hein & Co., but include any agreements and related documentation through consortia such as the Midwest Collaborative for Library Services (MCLS), the Big Ten Academic Alliance (BTAA), or Lyrasis.

Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of the “HeinOnline” database.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

title: Cybercheck communications and agreements

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Cybercheck communications and agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents since Jan. 1, 2024 between the Georgia Bureau of Investigation and Global Intelligence Inc. Dear Adam  Steinbaugh: 
This notice acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) received on 5/1/2025, in which you are seeking records related to the current policy, training, or guidance regarding the use of face masks, or other means, to conceal agents or officers identity. 

Please use the following unique FOIA tracking number CBP-FO-2025-115221 to track the status of your request.  If you have not already done so, you must create a SecureRelease account. This is the only method available to check the status of your pending FOIA request. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, CBP processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although CBP’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). As your request seeks documents that will require a thorough and wide-ranging search, CBP will invoke a 10-day extension for your request pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). If you would like to narrow the scope of your request, please contact our office.  We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

CBP’s FOIA Division is working hard to reduce the amount of time necessary to respond to FOIA requests.  We truly appreciate your continued patience. 
For additional information please consult CBP FOIA website please click on FOIA Act Resources or visit http://www.cbp.gov/site-policy-notices/foia. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 
Sincerely, 

U.S. Customs and Border Protection

communications.communication:
Adam  Steinbaugh 
n/a 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR185877 
263 Huntington Ave 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

08/05/2025 

CBP-FO-2025-115221 

DearAdam  Steinbaugh, 

This is a final response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP), requesting a ny current (as of the date of this request) policy, training, or guidance concerning any of the following by agents or officers of your agency or department: 

(a) Face masks (excluding policies relating only to public health or COVID-19), no records were found. 
(b) Concealed identity, no records were found. 
(c) Circumstances in which agents or officers must identify themselves to the public. The link is provided below. 

CBP is granting your request under the FOIA, Title 5 U.S.C. § 552.  Upon initial review of your request, we have determined that the following documents can be found on the internet at the following link: https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/2024-09/exhibit_09_-_cbp_use_of_force_policy_final_jan_2021.pdf 

This completes the CBP response to your request.  You may contact CBP's FOIA Public Liaison, Charlyse Hoskins, by sending an email via your SecureRelease account], mailing a letter to 1300 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW MS 1181, Washington DC, 20229 or by calling 202-325-0150. (If you need telecommunication relay service (TRS) assistance to communicate with the CBP FOIA Office and you are in the United States, please dial 711 to obtain TRS assistance and notify the Communications Assistant that you want to contact the CBP FOIA Office at the telephone number (202) 325-0150). The FOIA Public Liaison is able to assist in advising on the requirements for submitting a request, assist with narrowing the scope of a request, assist in reducing delays by advising the requester on the type of records to request, suggesting agency offices that may have responsive records and receive questions or concerns about the agency’s FOIA process. 

For your information, Congress excluded three discrete categories of law enforcement and national security records from the requirements of the FOIA. See 5 U.S.C. 552(c).  This response is limited to those records that are subject to the requirements of the FOIA. This is a standard notification that is given to all our requesters and should not be taken as an indication that excluded records do, or do not, exist. 

If you are not satisfied with the response to this request, you have a right to appeal the final disposition.  Should you wish to do so, you must file your appeal within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS regulations at Title 6 C.F.R. §5.8.  Please include as much information as possible to help us understand the grounds for your appeal.  You should submit your appeal via your SecureRelease account . If you do not have computer access, you may send your appeal and a copy of this letter to:  FOIA Appeals, Policy and Litigation Branch, U.S. Customs and Border Protection, 90 K Street, NE, 10th Floor, Washington, DC 20229-1177.  Your envelope and letter should be marked "FOIA Appeal." Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia.  Additional information can be found at the following link https://www.cbp.gov/sites/default/files/assets/documents/2019-Dec/definitions-exemptions-foia_0.pdf. 

Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS), which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769. Please note that contacting the CBP FOIA Public Liaison or OGIS does not stop the 90-day appeal clock and is not a substitute for filing an administrative appeal. 

Please notate file number CBP-FO-2025-115221 on any future correspondence to CBP related to this request. 

Please note that this message has been sent from an unmonitored e-mail account. Any messages sent to this account will not be read. 

Sincerely, 

U.S. Customs and Border Protection

title: Inspector General closed cases 2016 (Defense Intelligence Agency, Office of the Inspector General)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Inspector General closed cases 2016 (Defense Intelligence Agency, Office of the Inspector General)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

a copy of the list or printout or database listing of Inspector General investigations closed/reports completed during calendar year 2016. If the list is organized by FY rather than calendar year, the FY 2016 list is sufficient for this request. If no central list or database exists, then I request that the equivalent information be provided in the form of copies of the cover sheet or first page of each IG report completed during calendar year 2016.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best
